The liberalisation of abortion legislation was partially stalled by the pro-life phenomenon. Many women who have experienced abortion through illegal procedures abroad feel that they no longer have a place in society or cannot talk to anyone about it. Hence, those who have an abortion need emotional support. Recent statistical data suggests a slowly decreasing number of legal abortions after a peak in 2006-2007. The percentage of women who abort twice or more was 21 per cent in 2007, but it further declined to 14.7 per cent by 2012.

Taking into account the national peculiarities, the research also looked into the issue from a different perspective. Within the past few years, nanotechnology has been adopted as a contemporary means for the entirety of society. Founded upon an intersection between medicine, biology and engineering, this new discipline moves us towards a potentially scientific view of the human person. However, nanotechnology can also promote a fundamental uncertainty in relation to both bodies and human rights. Does nanotechnology raise the question of ‘human enhancement’ and thus confront a reality perceived by some people as a violation of the self?
